## Make scenario suites opt-in (excluded from routine/agent test runs)

Context: The `tests/e2e/scenarios/` journey suites are long and, for the
`*_live` ones, billable (warehouse + LLM + a durable registry write). They
must not run during routine development, the post-change routine, code
review, or Ask-mode test runs — only when the user explicitly asks. The live
scenario was already env-gated, but `test_full_lifecycle.py` was collected by
a plain `pytest` run. Introduced a `scenario` marker and made the canonical
agent test command exclude it, then propagated that convention into the
rules and skills.

Changes:

1. pyproject.toml
   Registered the `scenario` pytest marker in `[tool.pytest.ini_options].markers`.
2. pytest.ini
   Mirrored the `scenario` marker (kept in sync with pyproject per the file's own note).
3. tests/e2e/scenarios/conftest.py
   New conftest that auto-tags every test collected under `tests/e2e/scenarios/`
   with `pytest.mark.scenario`, filtering by path so the sub-dir hook does not
   tag the whole session's items.
4. .cursor/08-testing-and-deployment.mdc
   Documented the default/routine command `uv run pytest -q -m "not scenario"`
   and that scenarios are opt-in (`-m scenario`; live one also needs
   `ONTOBRICKS_SCENARIO_LIVE=1`).
5. .cursorrules
   Updated both "Run all tests" steps (post-change routine + code review) to
   use `-m "not scenario"` and point at `.cursor/08`.
6. .claude/skills/changelog/SKILL.md
   Post-change test step + the `Tests:` template now use `-m "not scenario"`.
7. .claude/skills/code-review/SKILL.md
   Review test step now uses `-m "not scenario"`.

Modified files:
- pyproject.toml
- pytest.ini
- tests/e2e/scenarios/conftest.py
- .cursor/08-testing-and-deployment.mdc
- .cursorrules
- .claude/skills/changelog/SKILL.md
- .claude/skills/code-review/SKILL.md

Tests: `uv run pytest -q -m "not scenario"` → 2998 passed, 58 failed, 17 skipped, **2 deselected** (the scenario suites, as intended). The 58 failures are pre-existing and unrelated to this change: a full-suite pytest-asyncio ordering issue (`RuntimeError: Runner.run() cannot be called from a running event loop` across `tests/units/api/*` and `tests/mcp/integration/*`) plus flaky Playwright timeouts in `tests/e2e/navigation/`. Verified inert: `tests/units/api/test_comment_endpoints.py` passes 8/8 in isolation, and collection checks confirm only the 2 scenario tests are deselected (`-m scenario` → 2 selected / 3073 deselected).

## Add scenario 2 — collaboration + review lifecycle (reuses scenario 1's domain)

Context: New live, gated journey that exercises the human-in-the-loop workflow
on top of a built domain. It deliberately **reuses the durable
``test_scenario_1`` domain** (built + persisted by scenario 1) rather than
regenerating one, then walks: add comments (ontology + mapping framing) →
turn them into tasks → advance a task → submit for review (DRAFT → IN-REVIEW)
→ reopen to DRAFT + new comment → publish (submit → sign-off → publish →
PUBLISHED) → create a new version (V2). Mapped each step to the real
internal API (``/comments/*``, ``/review/*``, ``/domain/create-version``).
Key constraints honoured: ``submit`` requires a prior KG build (``last_build``),
comments are writable only in DRAFT/IN-REVIEW, publish needs an IN-REVIEW
version (admin meets the quorum via a self sign-off).

Changes:

1. tests/e2e/scenarios/test_scenario_2_collab_lifecycle.py
   New scenario. Gated by ONTOBRICKS_SCENARIO_LIVE=1 + the `scenario` marker
   (auto-applied by the scenarios conftest). Skips with guidance when
   `test_scenario_1` is absent, never built, or already has versions > 1
   (re-run scenario 1 for a clean single-version V1). Idempotent for the
   comment/review steps (reopens V1 to DRAFT at start); creates V2.

Modified files:
- tests/e2e/scenarios/test_scenario_2_collab_lifecycle.py (new)

Tests: `ONTOBRICKS_SCENARIO_LIVE=1 uv run pytest tests/e2e/scenarios/test_scenario_2_collab_lifecycle.py -m scenario -v -s --no-cov` → **1 passed in 49.03s** (V1 PUBLISHED with 3 comments + 2 tasks, V2 DRAFT). Routine suite unaffected (new test is `scenario`-marked → excluded from `-m "not scenario"`).

## Consolidate 0.5.x → 0.6 Lakebase upgrade into a single clean script

Context: The `scripts/upgrade_lakebase_0.5_To_0.6.sql` migration created
`domain_comments` in the early, *anchored* 0.6 shape (`anchor_type` /
`anchor_ref` columns + `idx_domain_comments_anchor`). Discussions later became
domain-wide within the 0.6 cycle, so reaching the final schema required a
second pass, `scripts/upgrade_lakebase_0.6_drop_comment_anchor.sql`. A user
upgrading "0.5.x → 0.6" therefore had to run two scripts and briefly
materialise dead columns. Folded the anchor-drop into the main script so it
lands the final 0.6 shape (matching the canonical
`src/back/objects/registry/store/lakebase/schema.sql`) in one idempotent pass.

Changes:

1. scripts/upgrade_lakebase_0.5_To_0.6.sql
   - `domain_comments` now created in its final (anchor-less) form.
   - Added a converge step that `DROP INDEX IF EXISTS idx_domain_comments_anchor`
     and `ALTER TABLE ... DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS anchor_type / anchor_ref`, so
     installs already created with the anchored shape (earlier draft, app lazy
     self-heal, or `make bootstrap-lakebase`) converge cleanly. The
     `anchor_type` CHECK drops with its column.
   - Replaced the now-irrelevant `idx_domain_comments_anchor` with
     `idx_domain_comments_lookup (domain_id, version, created_at)`.
   - Removed the dead `anchor_type` CHECK backfill block; fixed the stale
     "see 1b" cross-reference in the `domain_tasks` status-CHECK backfill.
   - Rewrote the header to document the one-shot path and that
     `upgrade_lakebase_0.6_drop_comment_anchor.sql` is no longer required
     (kept only for installs already on the intermediate anchored 0.6 shape).
   - Part 2 (graph `datatype` / `lang` backfill) unchanged.

Note: no schema change was needed for the per-table SELECT "Rights" feature —
`can_select` / `select_error` live in the version `info` JSONB blob, not a
column.

Modified files:
- scripts/upgrade_lakebase_0.5_To_0.6.sql

Tests: not run — SQL-only migration script + changelog, no Python touched. The
script mirrors the canonical `schema.sql` and is idempotent (`IF EXISTS` /
`IF NOT EXISTS` guards throughout).

## In-place "update deployed app" script (code + SQL) reusing live config

Context: Updating an already-deployed OntoBricks instance (e.g. pushing the
latest code + applying pending registry migrations to `ontobricks-060`)
required editing `scripts/deploy.config.sh` and running `make deploy`. We
wanted a one-command updater whose ONLY inputs are the two app names, that
reads every coordinate back from the live apps so it never drifts from
`deploy.config.sh`. Built it to reuse the existing orchestrators rather than
duplicate them.

Changes:

1. scripts/update-deployed-app.sh (new)
   `update-deployed-app.sh <UI_APP> <MCP_APP>`. Introspects each app via
   `databricks apps get -o json` for its SQL warehouse, registry Volume
   (catalog.schema.volume), and Lakebase postgres binding (project / branch /
   db-… segment); fetches the deployed `app.yaml` (UI + MCP) verbatim via
   `databricks workspace export` so the runtime env (LAKEBASE_SCHEMA /
   LAKEBASE_DATABASE, triplestore table, MLflow URI, …) is preserved; then
   delegates the code push to `scripts/deploy.sh -t <target> --skip-app-yaml
   --no-bootstrap` and the SQL/grants to `scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`
   with the introspected schema. Volume-only apps skip the SQL step. Mirrors
   `deploy.sh`'s output/error-trap style.
2. scripts/deploy.config.sh
   Made `REGISTRY_SCHEMA` env-overridable (`${REGISTRY_SCHEMA:-$DEFAULT_…}`)
   so the new script can pin the schema it read back from a live app. Safe:
   every `make` deploy target already `unset`s `REGISTRY_SCHEMA`, so the
   routine deploy still uses `DEFAULT_REGISTRY_SCHEMA`.
3. scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh
   Extended the idempotent step-2b registry migration to also provision
   `domain_comments` + `domain_tasks` in their final (anchor-less) 0.6 shape
   (converging any pre-existing anchored table), so both `make deploy` and the
   new in-place updater provision the collaboration tables as the schema
   owner instead of relying on the app's lazy self-heal.

Modified files:
- scripts/update-deployed-app.sh (new)
- scripts/deploy.config.sh
- scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh

Tests: not run — shell/SQL tooling only, no Python touched. Validated with
`bash -n` on all three scripts (syntax OK) and verified `deploy.config.sh`
honours both the `REGISTRY_SCHEMA` override and the `unset` (default) path.
